Rating: 3
Very nice recipe. Very high result/effort ratio. The spices meld very well with each other. I added some white wine to the roasting pan about half-way and used the drippings for basting. To finish off the hens, I broiled them for about 2-3 minutes to get the skin crispy.

Rating: 3
I've made this twice and both times it was fabulous. I roast the hens whole instead of quartering and I save the pan drippings, add a little extra spice rub, chopped shallots, some chicken stock, and white wine, and reduce to make a spicy savory gravy. I serve them with roast cinnamon rubbed sweet potatoes and wilted greens. Yummy!

Rating: 3
I made this for supper after work and after exercising the dogs for an hour on a very hot humid day. An excellent choice, it was easy to prepare and was delightfully pungent. The suggested carrot salad made for a refreshing foil, and the nuts in the couscous added texture.

Rating: 4
I made this for the first time and my guests loved it. I cut the hens in half, used powdered ginger in lieu of fresh, and added a splash of OJ to the paste mix. Served w/basmasti rice (slivered almonds, raisins, shredded carrots and orange zest)and steamed broccoli and had chilled orange slices sprinkled w/ground cloves and honey for dessert.

